8 plates loading...

Your friendly reminder to not skip leg day 🫡
.
Even though my leg cuts are LONG gone, I still get approached about my quads at least once a week.
.
As you can see, I didn't come out of the womb with tree trunks able to squat 405 lbs 😅 I had to work diligently to turn a weakness into my strength.
.
Here are some tips if you want to grow yours:
.
1. STOP skipping leg day.
There is nothing fun about walking funny for 3-4 business days and not being able to sit on the toilet, but it's part of the process 💁‍♂️ DO the work.
.
2. Compound movements > Isolations.
Leg extensions/curls have their place in a regimen, but the people with the smallest leg improvements are the people that do 3 sets of leg extensions, 3 sets of leg curls, and call it a day. Do a squat. Do a leg press. Do a deadlift of some sort. DO NOT pass on the hard stuff. 
.
3. Focus on the MUSCLE - not the Movement.
I ditched the barbell squat for a hack squat years ago and saw incredible results immediately. The squat is amazing for brute strength and power, but there are much better exercises for targeting your thighs. Also, find a foot position that works best for you. I like to keep my feet narrow and further down on the platform.
.
4. Ditch the EGO, and go DEEP.
Those 1/2 squats aren't going to grow your legs, my dude. Range of motion is king, not how much weight you can put on your shoulders. Reduce the weight until you are able to execute deep, clean reps. Make your hamstrings touch your calves. Maximize your muscle stimulus by going as LOW as you can when you're squatting.
.
5. Go HEAVY.
Once you have your form down, build your strength up. Loading the weight of a small vehicle is a great way to get the most out of your legs. You have to push yourself and literally fight for your life every rep if you want to grow like crazy.
.
Lastly, find what works for you!
Every one is different, and what works for me may not work for you.
